definition: "Blood urea nitrogen (BUN) measures the amount of nitrogen from urea — the primary end product of protein catabolism — circulating in the blood. The process begins in the liver: when amino acids from dietary protein or tissue breakdown are metabolized, the amino groups are removed and converted to ammonia, which is rapidly converted to urea in the liver via the urea cycle (a hepatic detoxification pathway). Urea diffuses freely throughout the body and is filtered at the glomerulus of the kidney and primarily excreted in urine. Because urea is both produced by the liver (dependent on protein intake and catabolism rate) and cleared by the kidneys (dependent on renal function and hydration), the BUN reflects the interplay of protein metabolism and kidney function simultaneously. BUN is a standard component of every basic metabolic panel (BMP) and comprehensive metabolic panel (CMP) and is invariably reported alongside creatinine. The ratio of BUN to creatinine (BUN:creatinine ratio) provides additional diagnostic information that neither value provides alone."
why_it_matters: "BUN is one of the most ubiquitous blood tests in medicine — present in every BMP and CMP — yet it is among the least explained. Most people are told their BUN is 'normal' or 'slightly elevated' without understanding what that means or what can change it. For longevity monitoring, BUN carries information in three distinct domains. First, as a kidney function marker: chronically elevated BUN alongside elevated creatinine confirms reduced kidney clearance, and BUN trends provide context for interpreting creatinine and eGFR. Second, as a protein catabolism marker: elevated BUN with normal creatinine, normal kidney function, and a high BUN:creatinine ratio often reflects high protein intake, excessive muscle breakdown (from intense training, illness, or surgery), or dehydration — states that have distinct health implications. Third, as an indirect metabolic marker: chronically low BUN can signal impaired liver urea synthesis from advanced liver disease, or severe protein malnutrition. The BUN:creatinine ratio is particularly useful for distinguishing kidney causes of BUN elevation from pre-renal causes (dehydration, low cardiac output) — a clinical distinction with very different management implications."

standard_range: "7–25 mg/dL (ranges vary by laboratory; some use 6–20 mg/dL)"
longevity_optimal: "10–18 mg/dL"
longevity_notes: "In longevity contexts, the upper portion of the BUN reference range (18–25 mg/dL) warrants investigation of protein intake, hydration status, and kidney function rather than automatic reassurance. BUN should never be interpreted in isolation — creatinine, eGFR, hydration status, dietary protein intake, and recent physical activity all affect interpretation. The BUN:creatinine ratio (normal 10:1 to 20:1) provides directional information: a ratio above 20 suggests pre-renal causes (dehydration, GI bleeding, high protein intake); a ratio below 10 suggests hepatic causes (liver disease impairing urea synthesis) or relative excess of creatinine (muscle breakdown). Very low BUN (below 7 mg/dL) in a person not on extremely low protein intake warrants investigation for liver function impairment — the liver may not be synthesizing urea normally."
